@KK

I am certainly one of those who relish the crunch, and for me, a big part of gaining that appreciation was to *stop* looking things up when I felt stumped. However, I very much agree that “it’s your puzzle”, to be solved however you want!

Mainly, thank you for being forthright about your experience with the puzzle, and acknowledging that it was too hard for you — rather than criticizing the puzzle/constructor, as so many other commenters do.

@KK

Wordplay includes entries that test the solver's knowledge of languages, vocabulary, and grammar.

Entries that you call trivia test the solver's knowledge of  everything else.  Quite the put-down of the record of human achievement.

Literacy means more 
than knowing how to read; 
it means being well read.

@AI in Pittsburgh
I think the distinction for me is between reasoning and memorization of facts. I would not reduce "the knowledge of everything else" to indicate only facts that are gained by rote memory, but also to include many other things, such as knowledge of how to reason, knowledge of how to find things out. 

I would consider knowing Coach Swinney's first name to be trivia, but I was able to figure it out by reasoning about the four crosses, none of which I knew by rote. For me, products of rote memory interact with wordplay in a crossword. And sometimes interact with other forms of knowledge, such as being able to reason by analogy (as in Art Heist).

@A scientist - It's funny, because whenever the answer to this clue is "seed(s)" these comment are replete with pedants pointing out that they're ARILs. I think I have linked to this same article the past to point out that "seed" is not wrong, even if they are ARILS, too.

I think this may be the first time I've seen ARILs clued this way, though. 

I long ago concluded that both answers are fine for the purposes of a crossword.

